metadata.name: Bon Voyage #14
metadata.description:
We’ve gathered on the dock. Mother wears a custom-made
suit, bold black and white checks, the skirt fitted tight. My
sister and I teeter beside her, two untethered buoys, dresses
buoyant in the breeze. With her hand shading her eyes, Mother
watches the ship, a sailing city crammed with waving couples
against a white, white exterior. Bon Voyage, Bon Voyage, we cry
to friends of Mother’s, the wife barely recognizable
beneath a veiled hat. Corks burst from champagne bottles;
shrieks as the bubbling liquid pours over hands and arms. The
ship departs with an exaggerated HONK. We huddle in the back
seat of the car. Let’s pretend we’re sleeping on the
ship’s deck chairs, we whisper, and imagine the evening
growing colder. Perhaps we’d cling together, our shivering
bodies wrapped in widely-striped towels. Two girls alone on a
boat, the water black and rushing past, lips salty.

— Tina Barry, from

metadata.name: Meridian #21
metadata.description:
Each output is generated by layering Blender renders.

'Meridian' attempts to capture some of the beauty and simplicity of Bauhaus design ideas. The addition of a line (or Meridian) to these simple shapes creates a colorful, striking design with an Art Deco vibe!

To download:
Click/tap 'open', then click/tap the image to make a "Download image" button appear. Click this button to download a 1500x2000px PNG.

metadata.name: Nullteilung #270
metadata.description:
Nullteilung is another exercise in suprematism and composition. Born from a series of exercises in subdevision and tesselation, it seeks to connect with the user through the creation of a sense of order and balance in the composition.

The term "Nullteilung" a German word that can be translated to "zero division" which is suggesative of the order and disorder paramount in the piece, working toward a goal of emotional and programmatic purity.

metadata.name: Artifact #10
metadata.description:
This project is about uncovering artifacts.

Each piece is determined by approximately 15 parameters. This allows for a multitude of possible forms, and each iteration is an artifact to be discovered within the multidimensional space.

This work is focused around discovery. It is about exploring the space of the algorithm, shedding light on its many forms, and sometimes finding artifacts of the real world embedded within them.

Technically, this work is a composition of three primary elements: Voronoi tessellations, orthographic projection, and the depth-sort algorithm.
The latter of these is integral to the rendering mechanism. It works intuitively, drawing distant objects before near objects, evaluating the distance of each object according to its geometric center. It does this precisely, and in doing so, it can produce interesting visual artifacts, drawing some shapes in an unexpected order.



This has been a fascinating study, bringing light to unreal shapes and forms, and uncovering artifacts in an impossible space.

I hope you enjoy it,
Nat Sarkissian





Technical Notes:
- Append “&mag=N” to the end of the URL in live mode to specify a resolution multiplier. It will render the image N times larger than the size of your window. If you have specified anything greater than 1, a download will start automatically once the rendering is done.

metadata.name: Fictional Cityscapes #8
metadata.description:
Some of the most stunning, and beloved, images are large cities, viewed from afar at the right angle, and preferably with some water in front. 

This project comes from my experiments with line art, and is slightly inspired by Hevey's amazing Dencity drop, which is on a different level to most generative art. 

The cities here are based on some fictional tower architecture and some unusual skies.

metadata.name: Tails of Majestic Creatures #121
metadata.description:
Excerpt from the Annuls of WorSAGE (the Worshipful Society of Adventurers and Generative Explorers) XXVII.Vol.2048

"Some of the fantastically colored reeds that grow in clumps along the banks of the Tezonian river have profoundly affected the local inhabitants' culture, and beliefs.

Legend tells of how there lived majestic creatures, that were so beautiful, and dazzling, that they greatly offended Nocturna - the Deity of the Night. After many unsuccessful attempts to get rid of them, usually foiled by the clever Majestic Creatures in elaborate ways, Nocturna cast a powerful spell upon them. This spell was extremely effective and made the Majestic Creatures plummet, with great speed, into the ground leaving only their tails to show.

The creatures then turned their energy to nature, and joined as one to become a deity of the natural world. They rise, and protect creatures from harm, especially during the night.

The reeds (tails) are held as sacred, and believed to have healing powers.

I have created this graphical study of the tails (exotic reeds) for your informational requirements and ocular interest.

128 images are planned to follow henceforth, subject to available minters."

s will save a 4000x4000 jpg of the image. 
g will convert to gray.
c will convert back to color.
m will save a 4000x4000 monochrome jpg of the image.

Coded in P5.js

metadata.name: 8x8 Pixel Creatures #152
metadata.description:
Pixel art is a highly relevant art form, which rarely gets the kudos it deserves from the wider art world. 

I wanted to include some small pixel art creations in another project I was working on. However, I got a bit carried away, and ended up creating a pixel creature generator.

I came to like these little pixel creatures, so I decided to share them, and give them a life on FxHash - I hope you like them too. 

There are a bunch of variations, and a reasonable chance one or two styles may never be minted, so mint away, and I hope you get a rare one. Also, minters get a share in future royalties of their mints, which may be cool in any reality where they become popular one day.

I'll probably reference these guys on other relevant art I produce, when it seems appropriate.

Coded in p5js.

metadata.name: Cradle #321
metadata.description:
Billions of years old, ancient remains decay across our Solar System. Mere transient visitors to our star, their ephemeral presence on our worlds is embodied in their creations. In the shadow of their megalithic constructions, we wonder what they might have brought to us.

They brought life.

----

Live mode controls:
'r' - change resolution
's' - save PNG
'f' - render at full speed
'space' - stop/continue rendering

The image quality gradually improves over time. The rendering speed is reduced by default - press 'f' for the maximum speed.

Rendering may be GPU intensive.

metadata.name: Fragmented triacontahedron with iPhone 5s #6

Title: Fragmented rhombic triacontahedron with model iPhone 5s
Media: Interactive WebGL, resolution variable

A randomized composition of digital artifacts. Scans of a plaster sculpture that has been deliberately shattered. A deconstructed 3d model of an iPhone 5s. Original photography, textures, screen captures and found images. Stream of consciousness text.

* Mouse to orbit. Scroll wheel to zoom.

metadata.name: Element #72
metadata.description:
Element is a generative series of pixelated mosaics that explores two contrasting styles of generative art. One style embraces imperfection and noise to simulate paint or other real-life textures, while the other produces digital outputs with precise forms.

The mosaics were inspired by the works of Hiroshi Kawano, one of the pioneers of generative art. They are generated by randomly placing rectangles inside a grid then applying a Markov-chain process multiple times. A hand-drawn and organic style is then incorporated using various techniques such drawing many rectangles with subtle variations in colour for a paint texture or adding different kinds of noise.

Please view in full-screen for the best experience.

Press [s] when the output is fully rendered to download it as a png file. The resolution can be set by adding for example "&s=2048" to the url for a 2048 x 2048 output.

Element was released as part of the Cure3 exhibition, generating vital funds for Cure Parkinson's medical research.

metadata.name: GRAVITATE #26
metadata.description:
Each piece in this collection is made from the simple concept of layering grids of circles. The varying grid sizes, circle sizes, positions and colors combine to create interesting dithering effects. There are seven color palettes in the algorithm and these range from low contrast, muted palettes (e.g. Mystic Sands) to high contrast, super saturated palettes (e.g. Inferno).

- - -

GRAVITATE is my first generative art collection and was made using only p5.js.

- - -

Commands:
Press `1` to save a low-res PNG 1200x1800
Press `2` to save a high-res PNG 4800x7200

Note that it may take up to 10secs for the image render to complete.

metadata.name: Labyrinth #20
metadata.description:
The beginning of life is an incessant dream, a kaleidoscope of surprising discoveries, a colorful labyrinth in which you are enclosed by indefinitely high walls or a void, which you have to pass on your own. The person who may later become a guide through the labyrinth is still hiding behind some wall, past another turn. The main goal is to find him. If you succeed...


But you will succeed.


© Victoria Crux, 2022
